EXTENDED POWER PURCHASE AGREEMENT
This EXTENDED POWER PURCHASE AGREEMENT (this “Agreement”), dated as of March 30, 2011, is entered into between Black Hills Wyoming, LLC, a Wyoming limited liability company (“Seller”), and Cheyenne Light, Fuel and Power Company, a Wyoming corporation (“Purchaser”) (each a “Party” and collectively the “Parties”).
RECITALS
WHEREAS, Seller wishes to finance, construct, own, operate, and maintain an electric generation facility to be known as Gillette Plant with a capacity of approximately 40 MW to be located near Gillette, Wyoming (the “Facility”).
WHEREAS, Purchaser is an electric utility company having a service territory in and around Cheyenne, Wyoming.
WHEREAS, Purchaser wishes to purchase and take from the Seller, and Seller wishes to sell and provide to Purchaser, a portion of the electrical energy and capacity available from the Facility on the terms and conditions of this Agreement.
WHEREAS, Seller and Purchaser are parties to an existing Power Purchase Agreement, dated as of February 16, 2001 and a current expiration date of August 31, 2011 ("Existing PPA").
WHEREAS, Seller and Purchaser desire to continue the purchase and sale of electric capacity and energy by entering into this Agreement to extend the term of the Existing PPA for an additional three (3) years without change to any other rate, term or condition of service under the Existing PPA.
NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants and agreements set forth in this Agreement, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and adequacy of which is acknowledged, the Parties hereby agree as follows:
AGREEMENT
SECTION 1 - DEFINITIONS
1.1 Defined Terms. Unless otherwise defined herein or in any exhibit, schedule, or appendix hereto, the following terms, when used herein or in any exhibit, schedule, or appendix hereto shall have the meanings set forth below.
“Actual Total Capacity” means the actual total net capacity of the Facility determined in accordance with Section 9.1.
“Affiliate” means, with respect to any Person, any other Person controlling, controlled by, or under common control with the first Person. The term “control” (including the terms “controlling”, “controlled by,” and “under common control with”) means the possession, directly or indirectly, of the power to direct or cause the direction of the management or the policies of a Person, whether through the ownership of voting securities, by contract, or otherwise.
“Agreement” means this Power Purchase Agreement and the Appendices hereto, which are hereby incorporated herein by reference.
“Annual Contract Minimum Amount” means 210,240 MWh measured as the sum of Available Contract Amount for each hour for each rolling 12-month period under this Agreement.
“Appendix” means an appendix attached to this Agreement.
“Available Contract Amount” has the meaning assigned to such term in Section 4.1.
“Billing Period” means each Month used for billing purposes pursuant to Section 10.
“Business Day” means any day except Saturday, Sunday, or a day observed by banks in New York, New York as a holiday.
“Claims” means any claims, judgments, losses, liabilities, costs, expenses (including reasonable attorneys’ fees), and damages of any nature whatsoever (except workers’ compensation claims) in relation to personal injury, death, or property damage incurred or made by third parties.
“Commercial Operation Date” means the date on which the last of the following occurs (a) the Facility first demonstrates an Actual Total Capacity of at least forty (40) MW pursuant to Section 9.1; (b) the Facility has completed all environmental tests that must be performed prior to commercial operation as required by applicable Laws; (c) the Facility has completed a continuous one-hundred, sixty-eight (168) hour operating run with no more than ten (10) Forced Outage Hours during such operating run; (d) performance tests have been completed per Section 9.1; and (e) Seller provides to Purchaser a certificate stating that the Commercial Operation Date has been achieved for the Facility.
“Commercially Reasonable Efforts” means, with respect to any purchase or sale or other action required to be made, attempted, or taken by a Party under this Agreement, that the level of effort in light of the facts known to such Party at the time a decision is made: (i) can reasonably be expected to accomplish the desired action at a reasonable cost; (ii) is consistent with Prudent Industry Practices; and (iii) takes into consideration, among other things, the amount of notice of the need to take such action, if any, the duration and type of the purchase or sale or other action, and the competitive environment in which such purchase or sale or other action occurs.
“Contest” means, with respect to any Person, a contest of (a) any Governmental Approval or any act or omission by Governmental Agencies or (b) the amount or validity of any claim pursued by or against such Person in good faith and by appropriate legal, administrative, or other proceedings diligently conducted.
“Contract Year” means, initially, the period commencing on the Commercial Operation Date and ending on the last Day of the calendar year in which the Commercial Operation Date occurs, and, subsequently, each 12-Month period thereafter.
“Control Center” means the generation control center of Purchaser, its Affiliates, or any other Person, as may be designated in writing by Purchaser from time to time as being the primary control center for communicating with the Seller with respect to the Facility; provided that such designation shall be reasonably acceptable to Seller.
“Day” means the twenty-four-hour (24) period beginning and ending at 12:00 midnight (Mountain Prevailing Time).
“Default Rate” has the meaning assigned to such term in Section 10.3.
“Delivery Start Date” means the current expiration date of the Existing PPA (i.e., August 31, 2011).
“Early Termination Date” has the meaning assigned to such term in Section 14.2.
“Effective Date” means the date of execution of this Agreement by the Parties hereto.
“Emergency Condition” means a condition or situation that presents an imminent physical threat of danger to life, health, or property.
“Facility” shall mean the Gillette Plant.
“Facility Power” shall mean power generated from the Facility.
“Facility Site” means the site on which the Facility is located, which is near Gillette, Wyoming.
“FERC” means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
“Financial Closing Date” means the date on which the documents relating to the financing of the construction of the Facility are executed and delivered and the initial borrowings from the Financing Parties are made thereunder.
“Financing Documents” means any document relating to the financing or refinancing of the acquisition, development, construction, ownership, operation, maintenance, or leasing of the Facility.
“Financing Parties” means institutions (including any trustee or agent on behalf of such institutions) providing debt financing or refinancing to Seller for the acquisition, development, construction, ownership, operation, maintenance, or leasing of the Facility.
“Force Majeure Event” means an event, condition, or circumstance described in Section 13.1.
“Forced Outage” means any condition at the Facility that requires immediate removal of the Facility or some part thereof from service, another outage state, or a reserve shutdown state. This type of outage results from immediate mechanical/electrical/hydraulic control system trips and operator-initiated trips in response to Facility conditions and/or alarms.
“Forced Outage Hour” means any hour in which a Forced Outage occurs or is continuing.
“Gillette Plant” means the gas-fired LM6000 with enhanced SPRINT technology simple cycle generating plant to be located near Gillette, Wyoming, together with all other equipment necessary for the generation and transmission of Net Electrical Output to the Interconnection Point including any additions or replacements thereof, to be constructed, supplied, or delivered at or to the Facility Site.
“Gillette Plant Heat Rate” means the full load net plant heat rate, High Heating Value (“HHV”) determined in accordance with Section 9.1. There will be a Summer and Winter Gillette Plant Heat Rate.
“Government Agency” means any federal, state, local, territorial, or municipal government and any department, commission, board, bureau, agency, instrumentality, judicial, or administrative body thereof having jurisdiction over the Facility, Purchaser, or Seller, as the case may be.
“Governmental Approval” means any authorization, consent, approval, license, ruling, permit, exemption, variance, order, judgment, decree, declaration, or regulation of or by any Government Agency relating to the acquisition, development, ownership, leasing, occupation, construction, start-up, testing, operation, or maintenance of the Facility, or to the execution, delivery, or performance of this Agreement by either Party.
“Governmental Impositions” prior to the Commercial Operation Date means any new or reduced governmental impositions imposed after the execution of the Agreement that increases the cost of constructing the Facility, including changes in or additions to sales tax, property tax, energy use tax, or other governmental or regulatory fees (including emissions allowances, charges, or expenses) directly associated with the construction, ownership, lease, or operation of the Facility that are adopted after the execution of this Agreement or that occur as a result of a change after the execution of this Agreement in the interpretation or enforcement by an applicable Government Agency of an existing Governmental Imposition. After the Commercial Operation Date, Governmental Impositions means any new or reduced governmental impositions imposed after Commercial Operation Date that increases the cost of producing energy from the Facility, including changes in or additions to an energy use tax, or other governmental or regulatory fees (including emissions allowances, charges, or expenses) directly associated with the ownership, lease, or operation of the Facility that are adopted after the Commercial Operation Date. Governmental Impositions does not include increases in existing taxes and/or fees after the execution of this Agreement.
“Hourly Contract Amount” has the meaning assigned to such term in Section 4.1.
“Interconnection Facilities” means the interconnection facilities that shall connect the Facility with the Interconnection Point as more fully described in Appendix A.
“Interconnection Point” means the physical point at which the Facility is connected with the bulk power transmission system at the Wyodak 230 kV substation located at the Wyodak Plant site near Gillette, Wyoming.
“Law” means any statute, law, rule, or regulation or any judicial or administrative interpretation thereof by a Government Agency having the effect of the foregoing, whether in effect now or at any time in the future.
“Lien” shall mean, with respect to any property of any Person, any mortgage, lien, pledge, charge, lease, easement, servitude, right of others, or security interest or encumbrance of any kind in respect of such property of such Person.
“Month” means a calendar month.
“Mountain Prevailing Time” means Mountain Daylight Saving Time when such time is applicable in Gillette, Wyoming, and otherwise means Mountain Standard Time.
“MW” means megawatt.
“MWh” means megawatt-hour.
“NERC” means the North American Electric Reliability Council or its successor.
“Net Electrical Output” means for any period, the electrical energy output, as measured in MWh at the electricity metering points, that the Facility is capable of producing during such period, as adjusted for station service requirements and electrical losses to the Interconnection Point.
"Original Delivery Start Date" means September 1, 2001.
“Person” means any individual, corporation, partnership, limited liability company, joint venture, trust, unincorporated organization, or Government Agency or any business entity whose existence may be authorized by a Government Agency.
“Point(s) of Delivery” means the point at which Seller shall deliver the capacity and energy that is subject to the Agreement to Purchaser, which shall be at the Purchaser’s choice of Wyodak or Stegall West 230 kV bus.
“Power” means Facility Power or Replacement Energy.
“Prudent Industry Practices” means any of the practices, methods, standards, and acts (including, but not limited to, the practices, methods, and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric power generation industry in the United States) that, at a particular time, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known or that should reasonably have been known at the time a decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result consistent with good business practices, reliability, economy, safety, and expedition, and which practices, methods, standards, and acts generally conform to operation and maintenance standards recommended by a Facility’s equipment, suppliers, and manufacturers, design limits, and applicable Governmental Approvals and Law.
“Replacement Energy” means firm (according to NERC requirements) electric energy provided to Purchaser, at the Replacement Energy Delivery Point, from sources other than the Facility in accordance with the requirements of Section 4.2.
“Replacement Energy Delivery Point(s)” means the Point(s) of delivery unless the Parties mutually agree, in writing, upon another point(s) of delivery, such agreement to specify other applicable delivery terms and conditions associated with the other agreed upon point of delivery, including the degree of firmness.
“Scheduled Maintenance Outage” means a time period during which a Facility is shut down, or for which the Net Electrical Output is derated for Facility maintenance in accordance with Section 5.2
“Taxes” means, with respect to any Person, all taxes, withholdings, assessments, impositions, duties, governmental fees, governmental charges, or levies imposed directly or indirectly by any Government Agency on such Person or its income, profits, or property, or measured by the volume or amount of consumption of fuel, the production of energy, or the provision of electric generation capacity, or gross revenue, gross receipts, or comparable measure thereof, and whether characterized as an ad valorem, sales, gross receipts, BTU, carbon, energy production, or other similar taxes.
“Term” has the meaning assigned to such term in Section 2.1.
“Tested Minimum Generation” means the actual minimum energy that can be produced by the Facility as determined in accordance with Section 9.1.
1.2 Interpretation. Unless the context otherwise requires:
(a) Words singular and plural in number shall be deemed to include the other and pronouns having masculine or feminine gender shall be deemed to include the other.
(b) Any reference in this Agreement to any Person includes its successors and assigns and, in the case of any Government Agency, any Person succeeding to its functions and capacities.
(c) Any reference in this Agreement to any Section or Appendix means and refers to the Section contained in, or Appendix attached to, this Agreement.
(d) A reference to a Party to this Agreement includes that Party’s successors and permitted assigns.
(e) A reference to a document or agreement, including this Agreement, includes a reference to that document or agreement as novated, amended, supplemented, or restated from time to time.
(f) A reference to any Requirement of Law means such Requirement of Law as amended, modified, codified, or reenacted, in whole or in part, and in effect from time to time, including, if applicable, rules and regulations promulgated thereunder.
(g) “Hereunder”, “hereof”, and “hereto” and words of similar import shall be deemed references to this Agreement as a whole and not to any particular section or other provision hereof or thereof.
(h) “Including (and with correlative meaning “include”)” means including without limiting the generality of any description preceding such term.
(i) Relative to the determination of any period of time, “from” means “from and including”, “to” means “to but excluding”, and “through” means “through and including”.
(j) If any payment, act, matter, or thing hereunder would occur on a Day that is not a Business Day, then such payment, act, matter, or thing shall, unless otherwise expressly provided for herein, shall occur on the next succeeding Business Day.
1.3 Technical Meanings. Words not otherwise defined herein that have well-known and generally accepted technical or trade meanings are used herein in accordance with such recognized meanings.
1.4 Headings. The headings contained in this Agreement are solely for the convenience of the Parties and should not be used or relied upon in any manner in the construction or interpretation of this Agreement.
SECTION 2 - TERM
2.1 Term.
A. This Agreement is binding on the Parties on the Effective Date.
B. Subject to this Agreement’s approval or acceptance for filing by FERC without material change or condition, Seller's obligation to sell, make available, and deliver to the Point(s) of Delivery, and Purchaser's obligation to purchase, schedule, and pay for electric capacity and energy hereunder, shall commence on the Delivery Start Date and shall continue in effect for a period ending on August 31, 2014 (the “Term”), unless otherwise extended or terminated in accordance with the provisions of this Agreement. So as to remove any regulatory uncertainty regarding this Agreement, Seller shall make the requisite filing with the FERC within thirty (30) Days of the Effective Date, and shall request that the Agreement be accepted for filing with an effective date sixty (60) Days from the date of filing and shall request that FERC waive its normal notice requirements to permit the effectiveness of this Agreement at that time. However, after the execution of this Agreement neither Party shall take any action to adversely effect approval of this Agreement by the FERC. In the event that the FERC issues an order not approving this Agreement in its entirety without change, the Parties shall exercise all Commercially Reasonable Efforts to amend this Agreement so as to accomplish the issuance of an appropriate order by the FERC.
SECTION 3 - COMMENCEMENT OF OPERATIONS
3.1 Delivery Start Date. Seller shall make Facility Power available to Purchaser on Delivery Start Date.
SECTION 4 - SALE AND PURCHASE OBLIGATIONS
4.1 Sale and Purchase of Facility Power. Subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, Seller shall make available and if scheduled by Purchaser, deliver to the Point(s) of Delivery, and Purchaser shall purchase capacity and if scheduled by Purchaser accept during each Hour on and after the Delivery Start Date, an amount of Facility Power, contingent on Facility availability and Purchaser Schedule.
(a) Available Contract Amount. Seller shall make available an amount of capacity at the Point(s) of Delivery equal to the lower of: (a) 100 percent of the Net Electrical Output of the Facility or (b) 40 MWh per hour. The result of this calculation is defined as the “Available Contract Amount”.
(b) Hourly Contract Amount. Any Available Contract Amount or portion thereof scheduled by Purchaser and delivered by Seller will be the “Hourly Contract Amount.” The Hourly Contract Amount does not have to be generated by the Facility, at Seller’s option.
4.2 Source of Power. All Power delivered hereunder shall be Facility Power, whether or not generated at the Facility.
4.3 Additional Energy. Seller may offer energy in excess of the Hourly Contract Amount on an as available basis at a price to be mutually agreed upon by the Parties. Purchaser shall have sole discretion in accepting such energy at the stated price.
4.4 Replacement Energy. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained herein, the Seller shall use best efforts to provide Replacement Energy when the Facility is unavailable. Replacement Energy shall be: (i) available at the Point(s) of Delivery unless Seller and Purchaser agree in advance to a Replacement Energy Delivery Point; and (ii) when notifying Purchaser of the circumstances causing the disruption and the expected duration of the disruption, Seller shall agree to provide Replacement Energy in the full amount of the anticipated shortfall from the Facility, and for the full duration of the expected disruption. If Seller makes Replacement Energy available under the energy payment terms of 8.1 (b), then Replacement Energy shall be included as Available Contract Amount whether or not Purchaser schedules energy associated with Replacement Energy and if energy is scheduled such amount will be Hourly Contract Amount. If Seller is unable to make Replacement Energy available under the energy payment terms of 8.1 (b), Seller shall use its best efforts to make Replacement Energy available at a minimum price and such Replacement Energy will be priced at the actual cost of Seller to acquire such Replacement Energy provided that such Replacement Energy will not be considered Available Contract Amount and Purchaser shall not be obligated to schedule and shall not be obligated to pay for such Replacement Energy unless scheduled.
SECTION 5 - OPERATION OF THE FACILITY
5.1 Operation and Maintenance of Facility.
(a) Seller shall operate and maintain, or cause the operation and maintenance of, the Facility in accordance with Prudent Industry Practices and otherwise in accordance with this Agreement. Seller shall seek the non-binding advice of Purchaser in the event that Seller desires to enter into a contract with a third party to provide for the operation and maintenance of the Facility; provided, in no event shall Seller be obligated to seek such advice with respect to a third party operator that is an Affiliate of Seller. Any third party operator shall be required by Seller to execute a confidentiality agreement with Purchaser, in form and substance reasonably satisfactory to Purchaser, and to provide evidence of insurance appropriate to its operation of the Facility.
(b) Seller shall inform Purchaser on a daily basis by 0500 (Mountain Prevailing Time) of the generation capability of the Facility and any limitations, restrictions, deratings, or outages affecting the Facility for the next two Days, and shall update it’s notice to the extent of any material changes in this information.
(c) Seller shall, during the Term, only employ appropriately qualified (as determined in Seller’s reasonable opinion) personnel for the purposes of operating and maintaining the Facility and coordinating operations with the Control Center.
5.2 Scheduled Maintenance.
(a) Prior to June 1 of each calendar year during the Term subsequent to the calendar year in which the Commercial Operation Date occurred, Seller shall provide to Purchaser a non-binding proposed schedule of times available for Seller to schedule maintenance outages and a statement of whether it intends to deliver Replacement Energy during such outages, provided that Seller shall not propose scheduled maintenance during the months of January, February, March, July, August, and December, and further provided that Seller and Purchaser shall mutually agree to the maintenance schedule.
(b) After the Scheduled Maintenance Outages have been scheduled in accordance with Section 5.2(a) above, Purchaser shall have the right to request changes to such schedule and Seller shall use Commercially Reasonable Efforts to accommodate Purchaser’s request, provided that Seller shall in no event be required to accept such request if the implementation of the requested schedule change could, in Seller’s reasonable opinion, invalidate, or impair Seller’s insurance policies or the success of any claims to be made thereunder, result in a breach or constitute an event of default under the Financing Documents or any other material agreement to which Seller is a party, or cause the Seller’s actions or performance hereunder to deviate from Prudent Industry Practices. If Seller is able to accommodate Purchaser’s request, Seller shall provide Purchaser with a notice to such effect, which notice shall include Seller’s estimate of any costs that would result from Purchaser’s request. Upon receipt of such notification from Seller, if Purchaser desires that Seller proceed with such changed schedule, Purchaser shall so notify Seller and Purchaser shall reimburse Seller for all costs incurred in good faith by Seller in proceeding with such changed schedule. If Purchaser does not notify Seller of its decision on or prior to the commencement of the Scheduled Maintenance Outage (as originally scheduled), or in any event within two (2) Days after receipt of Seller’s notice that Seller is able to accommodate the requested change, then Seller shall proceed with the pre-existing schedule.
5.3 Access and Information.
(a) Seller shall provide to Purchaser from time to time the following information with respect to the Facility:
(i) The manufacturers’ guidelines and recommendations for maintenance of the Facility equipment;
(ii) A report summarizing the results of maintenance performed during each Scheduled Maintenance Outage and any Forced Outage, and upon request of Purchaser any of the technical data obtained in connection with such maintenance;
(iii) Meter reading data from the Facility; and
(iv) If required by FERC or the Wyoming Public Service Commission for recovery of all or a portion of variable costs, Seller shall provide Purchaser the average actual fuel cost for each month. For clarity, this number shall not impact the calculation of the amounts owed Seller by Purchaser or owed by Purchaser to Seller per Section 8.
(b) Upon reasonable prior notice (in light of the circumstances) and subject to the safety rules and regulations of Seller, Seller shall provide Purchaser and its authorized agents, employees, and inspectors with reasonable access to the Facility Site and the Facility: (i) for the purpose of reading or testing metering equipment, (ii) as necessary to witness tests of Actual Total Capacity in accordance with Section 9, (iii) in connection with the operation and maintenance of the Facility and the Interconnection Facilities, and (iv) for other reasonable purposes at the request of Purchaser.
5.4 Permits; Compliance with Laws.
(a) Subject to the right of Contest, Seller shall, at its expense, acquire and maintain in effect, from any and all Government Agencies with jurisdiction over Seller and/or the Facility, all Governmental Approvals, in each case necessary for the construction, operation, and maintenance of the Facility in accordance with this Agreement.
(b) Subject to the right of Contest, Seller shall, at all times, comply with all Laws and Governmental Approvals applicable to it and/or to the Facility, including all environmental laws in effect at any time during the Term.
(c) Subject to the right of Contest, Purchaser shall, at all times, comply with all Laws necessary for Purchaser to perform its obligations under this Agreement.
(d) The Facility has its Permit for Construction from the State of Wyoming which will allow for unrestricted operation of the Facility 8,760 hours/year (or 8,784 hours/year during leap years).
5.5 Operating Procedures. Purchaser and Seller have developed and adopted written operating procedures (“Operating Procedures”). The Operating Procedures shall establish the protocol under which the Parties shall perform their respective responsibilities under this Agreement and shall include, but shall not necessarily be limited to, method of Day-to-Day communications, identification of Black Hills’ control area operator and the nature of the reserves provided by such control area operator, key personnel lists for Seller and Purchaser, Forced Outage and Scheduled Maintenance Outage reporting, procedures for capacity testing, and daily capacity level and energy reports. Operating procedures may be amended from time to time with written mutual agreement of the parties.
SECTION 6 - SCHEDULING, DISPATCH AND DELIVERY
6.1 Dispatch; Scheduling for Delivery.
(a) Prior to the first Day of each Month, Seller shall provide to Purchaser good faith projections for each hour of each Month of the amounts of Facility Power and Replacement Energy that shall be available for scheduling by Purchaser hereunder.
(b) Three (3) mutually-recognized prescheduling days immediately preceding the day or days that Power is to be delivered hereunder, Seller shall provide to Purchaser good faith projections for each hour of the amounts of Facility Power and Replacement Energy that shall be available for scheduling by Purchaser hereunder.
(c) No later than 6:00 a.m. (Mountain Prevailing Time) on each mutually-recognized prescheduling day immediately preceding the day or days Power is to be delivered hereunder, Seller shall inform Purchaser for each hour of the amount of Facility Power or Replacement Energy that will be available for scheduling by Purchaser hereunder.
(d) Purchaser will preschedule energy associated with this Agreement in accordance with regional preschedule practices as they may change from time to time as mutually agreed by the Parties. Notwithstanding the foregoing, schedules submitted after the regional preschedule time will be accommodated, if practicable.
(e) Purchaser shall submit schedules to minimize the number of starts such that the Facility is not started more than two (2) times per Day to meet Purchaser’s schedules.
(f) Purchaser will schedule a minimum of the Tested Minimum Generation of the Facility (approximately 32 MW) unless otherwise mutually agreed in any hour in which Purchaser schedules any energy. Seller will be the sole judge of when Purchaser will be allowed to schedule less than the Tested Minimum Generation of the Facility.
(g) If Purchaser does not preschedule the energy associated with this Agreement, Seller shall have the right to schedule such energy for its own purposes per Seller’s discretion.
6.2 Transmission and Ancillary Services Provisions.
(a) Through the Term of this Agreement, Seller shall be responsible for all transmission and ancillary service arrangements and costs required to deliver, on a firm transmission service basis, the Hourly Contract Amount to the Point of Delivery, including but not limited to, any electric losses, transmission service charges, or ancillary service charges in connection with the delivery of such power and energy to the Point of Delivery provided however that Purchaser pays Seller amounts calculated per Section 8.1 (b) for deliveries to Stegall West. Except as otherwise provided for herein, Purchaser shall be responsible for all transmission and ancillary service arrangements and costs required to deliver the Hourly Contract Amount from the Point of Delivery to Purchaser’s load.
(b) The Transmission Rate (TR) for deliveries to Stegall West will be $2/MWh unless reduced per Section 6.2 (c). There will be no charge for deliveries to the Wyodak Point of Delivery.
(c) At such time as Black Hills Corporation or its operating Affiliate which owns transmission in the vicinity of the Facility joins a Regional Transmission Operator, the charges in Section 6.2 (b) will be adjusted as a result of such Regional Transmission Operator membership, provided that in the event that Seller or its operating Affiliate and Purchaser do not belong to the same Regional Transmission Operator, the total transmission charges collected by Black Hills Corporation, its operating Affiliate which owns transmission in the vicinity of the Facility, and Seller from Purchaser will not exceed the amount detailed in Section 6.2 (b).
SECTION 7 - INTERCONNECTION; ANCILLARY SERVICES; ETC.
7.1 Interconnection Facilities. Seller shall operate, maintain, and control at Seller’s sole cost and expense all Interconnection Facilities located on the Facility Site up to the Interconnection Point.
7.2 Interconnection Point. Seller shall deliver Facility Power to Purchaser at the Point of Delivery.
7.3 Risk of Loss. As between the Parties, Seller shall be deemed to be in exclusive control (and responsible for any property damages or injuries to persons caused thereby) of the Hourly Contract Amount prior to the Point of Delivery or the Replacement Energy Delivery Point (as applicable) and Purchaser shall be deemed to be in exclusive control (and responsible for any property damages or injuries to persons caused thereby) of the Hourly Contract Amount at and from the Point of Delivery or the Replacement Energy Delivery Point (as applicable).
SECTION 8 - PAYMENTS
8.1 Power Payments. Except as expressly provided herein, for each Billing Period commencing on the Commercial Operation Date, Purchaser shall pay to Seller for Power delivered by Seller to Purchaser in accordance with this Agreement a capacity payment and an energy payment as follows:
(a) Capacity Payment. For each Billing Period Purchaser shall pay a capacity payment according to the following formula:
CPR X 40,000 kW + G
Where:

Any award of the arbitrator may be enforced by the Party in whose favor such award is made in any court of competent jurisdiction.

Black Hills Wyoming, LLC Market-Based Rate Tariff
1. Availability: Seller makes electric energy and capacity available for sale for resale under this rate schedule to any purchaser.
2. Applicability: This rate schedule is applicable to all sales of energy or capacity by Seller not otherwise subject to a particular rate schedule of Seller.
3. Rates: All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller.
4. Other Terms and Conditions: All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller.
5. Ancillary Services. Seller may make available to any purchaser the following ancillary services:
a. California ISO Region: Seller may offer regulation service, spinning reserve service, non-spinning reserve service, and contingency reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO.
b. Third-Party Provider: Seller offers third-party ancillary services, including Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service, Primary Frequency Response Service, and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization.
6. Effective Date: This tariff shall be effective on the date specified by the Commission.
7. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this tariff.
8. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority. Seller has received (i) waiver of the accounting and reporting requirements contained in 18 C.F.R. Parts 41, 101, and 141, except sections 141.14 and 141.15; (ii) waiver of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subparts B and C, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15, and 35.16; and (iii) blanket authorization for the issuance of securities and the assumption of liabilities. See Black Hills Generation, LLC, Letter Order in Docket No. ER01-1844-000 (June 22, 2001).
The Commission authorized Seller to engage in affiliate power sales with Cheyenne Light, Fuel and Power Company under the terms of a Power Purchase Agreement effective April 2013, with Seller acting as seller and Cheyenne Light, Fuel and Power Company acting as purchaser. See Black Hills Wyoming, LLC, 128 FERC 61,285 (2009). In Docket Nos. ER19-2529-000, et al., the Commission authorized Seller effective October 15, 2020, to engage in affiliate power sales with Cheyenne Light, Fuel and Power Company under the terms of the Wygen I Settlement Power Purchase Agreement, with Seller acting as seller and Cheyenne Light, Fuel and Power Company acting as purchaser. See Black Hills Wyoming, LLC, 173 FERC 61,040 (2020).
9. Seller Category. Seller is a Category 2 seller in the Northwest Region, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a). Seller is a Category 1 seller in the Central, Northeast, Southeast, Southwest, and Southwest Power Pool Regions, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a).

SECTION 1 - DEFINITIONS

"Agreement" means this Power Purchase Agreement and the Appendices hereto, which are hereby incorporated herein by reference.

(a) Capacity Payment. For each Billing Period Cheyenne Light shall pay a capacity payment according to the following formula:
CPR X 60,000 kW + G
Where:
CPR= the Capacity Payment Rate which shall be $21.22/kW-mo
Starting in the calendar year after the calendar year of the Delivery Start Date, the Capacity Payment Rate shall escalate by the change in the U.S. Consumer Price Index, US Average, all Items less Energy as published by the Bureau of Labor Statistics (or comparable replacement index to the extent this index is no longer published) for the month of October from the previous year less one percentage point, with a minimum annual escalation of one percent.
G = 82.4% of the total annual Governmental Impositions related to BHWs ownership or operation of the Facility divided by 12.

For Hourly Contract Amounts delivered to the Point(s) of Delivery: (EPR) X (HCA)
Where:
EPR = the hourly Energy Payment Rate which shall be the lesser of the mutually agreed upon price for the hour or the capped rate calculated by the following formula: FP X AT + ER Where:

ER = the initial Energy Rate shall be $2.73/MWh

8.2 Availability Credit. For the January Billing Period, which is billed in February of each year, an availability credit will be payable from BHW to Cheyenne Light if Unit availability is less than 95%. Such credit is as calculated below:
Where:
CPR X (1-AF) X 60,000 X 12
CPR = the Capacity Payment Rate as defined in Section 8.1.
AF = the Availability Factor which equals a decimal fraction (i) the numerator of which is the sum of the hourly Available Contract Amount for the previous twelve (12) Billing Months and (ii) the denominator of which is the product of 60 MW times 0.95 times the Page 11 number of hours in the previous twelve (12) Billing Months, provided that the Availability Factor shall never exceed one (1).
